377","1497":"1497","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Abt 1407":"omkring 1407","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Frystone, Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby Bridge, Jórvík, England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"1380–1414":"1380–1414","1377–1414":"1377–1414","1396–Female":"1396–Overleden","1396–Male":"1396–Overleden","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1400–1497":"1400–1497","1407–Male":"1407–Overleden","1359–1381":"1359–1381","1414":"1414","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1377":"1377","1497":"1497","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Abt 1407":"circa 1407","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Frystone, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1380–1414":"1380–1414","1377–1414":"1377–1414","1396–Female":"1396–Deceased","1396–Male":"1396–Deceased","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1400–1497":"1400–1497","1407–Male":"1407–Deceased","1359–1381":"1359–1381","1414":"1414","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1377":"1377","1497":"1497","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Abt 1407":"about 1407","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Frystone, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mares","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Luis, Mario, Ruben, Arturo, Guadalupe, Rafael, Ramon.","Catalan (<b>Marès</b>, also <b>Marés</b>): topographic name from Catalan <i>marès</i> ‘by the sea’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Le Marais-la-Chapelle (Calvados), Marais-Vernier (Eure), or various other minor places in northern France named with Old French <i>marais</i>, Norman-Picard <i>marese</i> ‘marsh’."],"variants":[{"name":"Maris","meanings":["English: variant of   Mares   2.","Flemish and Dutch: metronymic from the personal name <i>Marie</i> (see   Maria  ).","Dutch (<b>Van Maris</b>): habitational name for someone from Maris in Dutch Limburg."]},{"name":"Marschke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Otto.","German (Silesia, Saxony, and Bohemia): from a Germanized Slavic pet form of the Old Slavic personal name <i>Maroslav</i>, with the first element probably based on the root <i>mar-</i> ‘to ruin’, or of a personal name such as Czech and Slovak <i>Mareš</i> (see   Mares   4)."]},{"name":"Marez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Lupe, Jesus, Armando, Juan, Juanita, Leandro, Ruben, Adelfa, Alfredo, Amalia, Ana.","Hispanic: altered form of Catalan <b>Marès</b> (see   Mares  ), influenced by the Spanish patronymic suffix <i>-ez</i>.","French (Nord): variant of   Maret  ."]},{"name":"Merris","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mares   2."]},{"name":"Maria","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ana, Elena, Manuel, Pedro, Juan, Miguel, Rafael, Santa, Alejandro, Amado, Amandio.  Portuguese Joaquim.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Salvatore, Albertina, Antonino, Cataldo, Filiberto, Ignazio, Plinio, Sal.","Spanish (<b>María</b>); Italian and Portuguese; Hungarian (<b>Mária</b>): from the female personal name, Latin <i>Maria</i>. This was the name of the mother of Jesus Christ in the New Testament, as well as several other New Testament figures. The Latin form of the name, on which all common variants from European languages are based (including English   Mary  ), derived as a back-formation from the early Christian female name <i>Mariam</i>. This was mistaken for an accusative case, with the usual Latin feminine accusative ending <i>-am</i>, but in fact it is an Aramaic form (originally <i>Maryam</i>) of the Hebrew name <i>Miryam</i>. The Hebrew name is of uncertain etymology, perhaps from a word meaning ‘wished-for child’, from an Egyptian root <i>mrj</i> with the addition of the Hebrew feminine diminutive suffix <i>-am</i>. Saint Jerome understood it as a compound of <i>mar</i> ‘drop’ + <i>yam</i> ‘sea’, which he rendered as Latin <i>stilla maris</i>, later altered to <i>stella maris</i> ‘star of the sea’, whence the medieval Christian liturgical phrase.","French: Latinized form of   Marie  , a cognate of 1 above. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin."]},{"name":"Maresh","meanings":["Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Mareš</b> (see   Mares  )."]},{"name":"Marris","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mares   2.","Dutch: variant of   Maris   2.","Americanized form of Greek   Maris   4 or 5."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Mares was born in 1380, in Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Thomas de Mares. She married Robert Rawson in 1396, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1414, in her hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1380–1414":"1380–1414","1377–1414":"1377–1414","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1400–1497":"1400–1497","1407–Male":"1407–Surnud","1359–1381":"1359–1381","1414":"1414","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1377":"1377","1497":"1497","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Abt 1407":"umbes 1407","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Frystone, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1380–1414":"1380–1414","1377–1414":"1377–1414","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1400–1476":"1400–1476","1400–1497":"1400–1497","1407–Male":"1407–Kuollut","1359–1381":"1359–1381","1414":"1414","1359":"1359","1400":"1400","1476":"1476","1377":"1377","1497":"1497","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","Abt 1407":"noin 1407","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Frystone, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England":"Sowerby Bridge, Yorkshire, England","Fryston, York